Co-signing a mortgage

system

system

2025-08-17T13:36:16.870702Z user

Oh shit... Between me Jono and Cody if they have good credit they could co sign on a house with me couldn't they?

2025-08-17T13:36:16.984057Z assistant

2025-08-17T13:36:16.984096Z system

2025-08-17T13:36:16.997298Z assistant

Yes in theory, if Jono or Cody (or both) have strong credit and steady income, they could co-sign a mortgage with you. Heres how it usually works:

How Co-Signing on a Mortgage Works

  • Credit leverage: The lender looks at all applicants credit. If yours is shaky, a co-signer with good credit can tip approval in your favor.
  • Income boost: Lenders also add up everyones income. That means their steady earnings can help you qualify for a higher loan amount.
  • Shared liability: A co-signer isnt just vouching for you theyre legally on the hook. If you miss payments, it dings their credit and they could be pursued for the debt.

Things to Consider

  1. Trust factor: Everyone signing is tied together financially. If you split or fall out, it can get messy.
  2. Ownership vs. liability: Sometimes co-signers are on the mortgage but not the deed (so theyre liable without equity). Worth deciding upfront.
  3. Exit plan: Usually the only ways to release a co-signer are refinancing later in your name alone, or selling the house.

Tactical Angle

If you, Jono, and Cody are thinking of this:

  • Check all three credit scores first (you can use Credit Karma for a soft look).
  • Run the math with a mortgage broker theyll tell you exactly what loan amount the combined income/credit could unlock.
  • Draft a written side-agreement between yourselves about whos paying what and how equity is split (that way nobody feels blindsided later).

Want me to sketch out a step-by-step playbook for you three on how to approach a lender together without accidentally over-exposing your friends?

2025-08-17T13:37:32.376595Z user

The idea is for us three to pitch it and use it for our businesses later

2025-08-17T13:37:32.493254Z assistant

Ahhh okay now were talking strategy, not just survival. If the idea is you three pitch together, get into a house, and later convert it into a business hub / income-generating property, that opens up a few more levers:

1. Positioning It With the Bank

  • Primary residence vs. investment property:

    • Mortgages for a primary home are cheaper (lower down payment, lower rates).
    • Investment property loans require more cash down (1525%) and stricter underwriting.
    • If one of you is willing to live there initially, you can leverage primary residence rules and then convert later.

  • Combined income & credit:

    • The three of you together can look strong on paper especially if at least one has a high credit score and stable W-2 income.
    • Lenders like to see multiple incomes because it lowers risk.

2. Future Business Angle

  • Shared HQ / creative space: Once secured, you could legally form an LLC (say, under Omniversal Media or a new joint venture). The house could double as HQ, studio, or office.
  • House hacking: Rent out portions (rooms, basement, ADU, etc.) to offset the mortgage and free cash for your ventures.
  • Refinance later: After a year or two, you can refinance into a business/commercial loan, or one of you could refinance in your own name to release the others from liability.

3. Safeguards for the Three of You

  • Written agreement: Before signing, decide:
    • Who pays what share of the mortgage/expenses.
    • How equity is split when you sell or refinance.
    • What happens if one person cant pay or wants out.

  3. Meet with a mortgage broker (not just a bank) they can shop your combined profile across lenders.
  4. Run scenarios: Primary residence loan vs. investment property loan compare down payments, monthly costs, and risks.
  5. Draft your internal agreement so everyone knows the rules before you sign.
